AGI - In Georgia > the feeling is to be at a turning point > in the tormented history of this fair, but fragile, former Soviet Republic. Historical crossroads of civilizations between Europe and Asia, the country of not even four million inhabitants has always been the object of the geopolitical appetites of invisible neighbors: from the Persian Empire, passing through the Ottoman and Russian, up to the Bolsheviks. For more than a month, it is the fear of returning under the orbit of Moscow >, abandoning the path already undertaken to enter the European Union, to bring in the square every evening the population, despite the harsh repression of the police.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<
<div </div
</div
<h2> The heart of events </h2>
The capital of Tbilisi is the epicenter of protests. “The future of Georgia is at stake, we do not want to become a Russian protectorate, our Constitution establishes both European integration and NATO membership, the government cannot put them at risk,” warns Tamara Kvaratshelia>, a young researcher who, in one of the last days’ demonstrations in Piazza della Liberta, together with a noisy whistle, held the sign “No to Putinistan!”. To unleash the anger of this varied movement without leader - led mainly by the young people of Generation Z >e composed of opposition parties >, associations of civil society, but who saw the participation of pensioners and some priest of the local Orthodox Church - was the introduction in Parliament, a few months from the general elections of next October 26, of the infamous foreign influence law, which Brussels considers a threat to the path of integration.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>The Russian law which has unleashed anger></h2>
Presented in April after the government had had to withdraw it last year for strong popular dispute, the law was approved on 14 April in the third and final reading by the majority and allies: for Ong and media > which receive more than 20% of their foreign revenue the obligation to register with the Ministry of Justice > as "organisations serving the interests of a foreign power".&nbsp;The promoter of the initiative is the government party Georgian Dream >, founded by oligarca&nbsp;Bidzina Ivanishvili, who made his fortune in the 1990s in Russia; has been presented as a necessary tool to ensure transparency of funds flows and to combat the “ pseudo-liberal values” promoted by abroad through the opposition, which in turn would aim at a supposed coup and drag Georgia into a conflict with Moscow.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
< blockquote
For civil society, the measure is simply known as “Russian law” > due to the similarity with the infamous “law on foreign agents” with which from 2012 Moscow silences the critical voices of power
</blockquote
&nbsp;
The same indistinct accusation to the NGOs - whose foreign funds mostly arrive from the theoretically allied countries of Tbilisi, i.e. Usa and Ue - to work for foreign powers brings back to memory the Soviet times, when the expression was used to stamp spies and enemies of the people.&nbsp; The law, among other things, provides for surprise inspections and fines that can reach up to the consideration of 9,000 euros.
<h2 Government between EU integration promises and admissions to Moscow ></h2>
Russian aggression against Ukraine on 24 February 2022 accelerated the EU membership process not only in Kiev and Chisinau, but also in Tbilisi. Meanwhile, Turkish influence and historical partners such as Armenia have grown in the Caucasus, starting to get away from the Kremlin. Russia – which already controls 20% of the Georgian territory in the Independent Republics of South Ossetia and Abkhazia – “has all the interest in strengthening its position in the region and the current Georgian government seems ideal for doing so,” explains in anonymous form a Georgian analyst working for an international organization in the region. Georgian dream, in power since 2012, has always tried to find a balance between the stabilization of ties with Moscow and formal support to the goal of Euro-Atlantic integration, supported according to the polls from 81% of the population.> Tbilisi condemned the Russian invasion, but did not adhere to Western sanctions and provided only humanitarian aid to Kiev; despite not having diplomatic relations with the Federation after the war of 2008, he reestablished direct flights with Moscow; he has a very permissive visa regime with the Russians (he received, according to some estimates, at least 100,000 escaped after the invasion), but also refused entry to several political opponents of the Kremlin; recently, he promoted a measure to facilitate the return of offshore capital that according to the opposition, will favour Ivanishvili and oligarchs willing to save from punitive measures their assets in the West, with the risk of turning the country into a hub of dirty money.
&nbsp;
Other signals that indicate an illiberal revolution of the government and its potential rapprochement to Russia come from a bill, always presented by Georgian Dream in March, and limiting the rights of Lgbt> people. The move was read as an attempt to increase consensus in a very conservative society, in view of the appointment at the October urns, but it recalls very much the policies against “gay propaganda” of Russian mold.
<h2> A "turn" of foreign policy
With the law on foreign influences, Georgian Dream “broken &nbsp; its traditional strategic ambiguity and gave a turning point to national foreign policy, redirecting the country towards Moscow”, according to Ana Tavadze, 26 years, responsible for developing the Ong Shame (Vergogna), in the first row in the organization of protests. The office of Shame, in one of the streets of the old town of Tbilisi with the classic lacumbered wooden balconies, is full of EU flags, anti-gas masks and skies to protect itself from tear gas and rubber bullets used by police against anti-Putin protesters and stickers; one depicts the face of the leader of the Kremlin, covered by two boots prints; activists attacked him under the toilet in the bathroom, so that anyone sits simultaneous the gesture of trampling the politician who more than all threatens their future.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
“Ivanishivili made a rare public speech at the end of April, in which he threw the mask,” said Tavadze, “it was a turning point for foreign policy, &nbsp; because he directly attacked the West, holding it behind the so-called ‘global war party’, which wants to destroy the identity and sovereignty of Georgia.” In the same speech Ivanishvili, former Prime Minister and considered the true leader of the country, announced repressions against opponents, mainly the United National Movement, whose president Levan Khabeishvili was beaten to blood by the agents, during the demonstrations of two weeks ago.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The proposal for the Foreign Influence Act came in a coordinated way with similar proposals in other countries such as Slovakia,&nbsp; Serbian Republic of&nbsp; Bosnia and Herzegovina &nbsp; and Kyrgyzstan. “It’s an action coordinated by Moscow,” says Shame’s activist, who says the first goal of Georgian Dream is to ensure that they remain in power, hitting first of all le&nbsp;Ong who are responsible for monitoring the October vote, independent media and realities that trace corruption and wealth of the ruling class. The violence used openly by the police to suppress protesters, > in the square and in the commissioners, as well as the burst of anonymous threats and aggression against activists, is another element that makes Tbilisi's move towards "Russian methods", denounces Tamar Oniani, director of the Human Rights program of one of Georgia's longest-lived NGOs, the Association of Young Lawyers. EU, USA and NATO have condemned the brutal repression of peaceful protesters and called for the withdrawal of the law on foreign influences, warning that "it would further release Georgia from European and European-Atlantic integration", as the Alliance spokesman, Farah Dakhlallah.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The European Union is the main donor of the country, with support for reforms that amount to more than 120 million euros a year. The US, from 1991 to 2020, has invested more than US$4.4 billion for the democratization and defense of Georgia, according to a Congressional Research Service report. If Washington has condemned the anti-Western path undertaken by Tbilisi, threatening economic sanctions and travel; the EU has criticized the violence on protesters and clearly indicated the incompatibility of the law with European values, but without mentioning punitive measures. According to many activists, the EU's approval of Georgia's candidate status in December - without this having made substantial progress on most of the recommendations indicated by Brussels - gave rise to Ivanishvili's party to resume the controversial measure on foreign influences.
&nbsp;
The law is now on the table of Salomè Zourabichvili, the president entered in total collision course with the government and who has already announced his veto. The executive, however, can easily circumvent it when the measure returns to Parliament, thanks to the numbers it has. The possibility, if Tbilisi asks, to study with the EU amendments to the law that make it acceptable and, for example, cancel the indiscriminate stigmatization of "foreign agent" for all NGOs, without distinction between political and social activities. Indications in this sense could come from the immediate opinion on the disputed law by the Commission of Venice, body of the Council of Europe.&nbsp; Prime Minister Irakli Kobakhidze, said he was available to evaluate changes, >while the President of the European Council, Charles Michel, has just promised to help Georgia “find the best way to address the legitimate concerns of all parties.” The eyes remain on October, when the European Commission will present its opinion on the progress process with respect to the reforms requested and may not confirm the status of candidate.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The fears of the future of a young democracy </h2>
The NGOs have already stated that they will not register if the law enters into force, the square has warned that it will not accept any amendment and that it will only settle when the document is withdrawn. Meanwhile, apprehension is growing not only for the European future of Georgia, but also for its security and health itself of its democracy. For many of the Georgians who have experienced the USSR and speak perfectly Russian but even more for young people, who have never been to Moscow and are accustomed to travelling in the EU, thanks to the abolition of visa obligation, being integrated in Western institutions is the only way to mitigate the Russian threat and guarantee the sovereignty of the country.
&nbsp;
“All Georgia’s foreign policy has always been a continuous security research,” he points out.Dachi Imedadze, 25 years old, also a member of the Ong Shame, “we know that the EU is not NATO, but it will still increase our defence.” “With the entry into Europe I hope that my country will finally have strong and independent institutions that will contribute to its democratization and social development”, is the hope of activist Nino Bochoridze, tra&nbsp; organizers of a recent anti-government event in Telavi, a city traditionally less prone to mobilization. Levan, a smiling man &nbsp; on the sixteenth, produces wine in Kakheti, the most famous wine region of Georgia, where the traditional method involves winemaking in the &nbsp;qveri, great terracotta amphoras, buried. In Sighnaghi - the second largest city in this eastern part of the country, also known as the “Georgian Tuscan” - the main street is covered with EU flags. Levan does not want to be quoted by his real name, but it is explicit when he notes that Georgia “has no choice but Europe”, to avoid returning to live as during the USSR, “just inside a prison”. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
