AGI - G<span> European consumers have accused the Chinese Temu app of using “handling techniques” to force users to spend more.” </span
The European Consumer Rights Group BEUC lodged a complaint with the European Commission, while 17 European organisations, including France, Germany and Spain, did the same with the national authorities.
&nbsp;
Groups accuse Temu of “not protecting consumers and using illegal manipulation practices”, known as “dark patterns”, and ask for an investigation.
They believe that Temu is distorting or compromising the ability of consumers to take “free and informed decisions” during online purchases, in violation of the EU’s mastodontic online content law known as Digital Services Act (DSA)>.&nbsp;According to the BEUC, the platform does not provide sufficient information about the traders present on Temu, “leaving consumers often in the dark of those who are buying.”
&nbsp;
Temu, one of the fastest growing apps, entered the EU market only in April 2023 and claims to have on average about 75 million active users per month in the block of 27 countries.
Based on the DSA, all digital platforms must quickly remove illegal content, be more transparent on how they use user data and ensure the security of online buyers.
&nbsp;
In addition, there is not enough information about the operation of its “opaque” recommendation system, which is mandatory under the DSA.
Temu, owned by Chinese PDD Holdings, has already undergone pressure in Europe.
&nbsp;
At the beginning of this year German consumer groups warned Temu from similar issues, and the platform announced that it would no longer see warnings inviting consumers to “Sbrigarsi! More than 126 people have this item in their cart.” The company has also faced severe control in Asia and the United States.
In April, South Korean regulatory authorities began investigating Temu for suspected misleading advertising and unfair practices.
